english:
  title: Rhyme
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A poor man has suffered eye ailments for three years now,
    And troubles have compounded his misery all the while.
    Now you close your door and darken your sight—
    How can we share the same heart yet bear the same affliction?

    Not to see things brings no true harm;
    The mind within carries its own luminous mirror.
    Forget the books—they are but the dregs of doctrine,
    Let dusty volumes and worm-eaten pages languish behind walls.
    Heaven merely plays tricks on us poor souls;
    What is blindness but a detail among the hundred years?

    At dawn I wade through dewy grass along the eastern hedge,
    Where golden chrysanthemums blaze in brilliant clusters.
    I summon wine and pour cup after cup,
    The wildness of youth still burns fierce and unbound.
    Fools warn: "This is the road to darkness!"
    "Daily intoxication cannot be called virtue."

    Smash the wine cup with a hammer, they counsel,
    Practice restraint and fortune will surely follow.
    Yet autumn flowers wither once more,
    Not a single blossom remains fresh and fair.
    Tomorrow I too shall be old;
    Once decay sets in, can it bloom again?

    Why abstain from wine for a minor ailment?
    Why silence my verses for fear of reproach?
    Life and death—both fall within a hundred years.
    Why cling so desperately to worry and woe?
    Let us face each other and raise the great vessel high;
    Only then can this discourse reach its fitting end.
  footnotes:
    - The poem is addressed to a friend who has also fallen ill with blindness and withdrawn from society. Park Eun employs the shared affliction as a metaphor for broader life's burdens and disappointments.
    - The 'eastern hedge' and 'golden chrysanthemums' echo the classical Chinese tradition of the recluse poet, suggesting a retreat into nature and simple pleasures rather than worldly concerns.
    - The extended meditation on wine, restraint, and virtue reflects Neo-Confucian moral discourse of the period, which Park Eun both acknowledges and gently subverts through his emphasis on shared joy and acceptance of fate.
